FAQs
What are the eligibility criteria for study medicine in Italy?

Applicants typically need to have completed their secondary education with strong grades in science subjects and demonstrate proficiency in English. Specific requirements may vary by university.

How much does it cost to study medicine in Italy?

Tuition fees for medical programs in Italy range from €1,000 to €4,000 per year. Living expenses typically range from €700 to €1,200 per month.

Are there scholarships available for international students?

Yes, many Italian universities offer scholarships based on academic merit. Additionally, the Italian government and private organizations provide various scholarship opportunities for international students.

What is the application process for medical schools in Italy?

The application process involves submitting an online application through the university’s portal, along with academic transcripts, a personal statement, letters of recommendation, and proof of English proficiency. Be sure to check each university’s specific deadlines.

Can international students work while study in Italy?

International students in Italy are allowed to work part-time for up to 20 hours per week during the academic year and full-time during holidays. This provides an opportunity to gain work experience and support their living expenses.
